<body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:36.0pt'>

<p><strong> Naturalism in Literature and Cinema</strong></p>
<p><strong>Prof. D. Trotter  (Fri 2 pm, Weeks 2-7, Lent Term) </strong></p>
<p>There will be screenings of all films listed under &lsquo;Prescribed viewing&rsquo;. </p>
<p> <strong>1.</strong>	Naturalism Then</p>
<p><strong>1.1.</strong> Prescribed viewing</p>
<p>There is no prescribed viewing for this class.</p>
<p><strong>1.2.</strong> Prescribed reading</p>
<p>Frank Norris, <em>McTeague </em>(1899), ed. Jerome Loving (World&rsquo;s Classics, 1995)</p>
<p>Georges Bataille, extracts from&lsquo;Critical Dictionary&rsquo;, in Encyclopaedia Acephalica,
  ed. Alastair Brotchie (London: Atlas, 1995) (photocopies supplied)</p>
<p>  <strong>1.3.</strong> Further viewing</p>
<p>D.W. Griffith, 'A Corner in Wheat' (1909)<br>
  Eric von Stroheim, <em>Greed</em> (1924)<br>
  Cecil B. de Mille, <em>The Cheat</em> (1915)</p>
<p><strong>1.4.</strong> Further reading</p>
<p>Becker, George J., ed., <em>Documents of Modern Literary Realism</em> (Princeton: Princeton
  UP, 1963)<br>
  Theodore Dreiser, <em>Sister Carrie</em> (1900)<br>
  Frank Norris, 'A Deal in Wheat' (1902), in <em>The Best Stories of Frank</em> <em>Norris </em>(New York: Ironweed Press, 1998) <br>
  <em>Responsibilities of the Novelist and Other Literary Essays</em> (New York:
  Haskell, 1982)<br>
Emile Zola, <em>L&rsquo;Assommoir</em> (1877), <em>Nana</em> (1879)</p>
<p><strong>1.5.</strong> Criticism</p>
